The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Soccer fans clash after match
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Soccer fans clash after match
          A STAFF REPORTER                              
	Fans of two Maidan soccer clubs fought a pitched battle in Topsia on Sunday afternoon, spreading panic among residents and disrupting traffic on Gobinda Khatik Road and the Park Circus-EM Bypass connector. Three men were injured and two local clubs were ransacked.        
	The situation was brought under control after Rapid Action Force personnel reached the spot and lathicharged the protesters. No one has been arrested.        
	The clash broke out when supporters of Mohun Bagan and Mohammedan Sporting were returning home from the Salt Lake stadium  where the two clubs locked horns in a Calcutta Premier League match that ended in a draw  in two lorries.        
	The groups started teasing each other at the Chingrihata crossing of the EM Bypass. The situation worsened after the groups entered Gobinda Khatik Road, near the Park Circus No. 4 bridge. The Mohun Bagan supporters allegedly ransacked a club that was set up by Mohammedan Sporting supporters, said an officer of Topsia police station.        
	As news of the ransacking spread, more than 100 Mohammedan Sporting supporters from the locality attacked youths loyal to the rival club. The violence soon spread to the terminus of route 24 bus-es, where a club set up by Mohun Bagan supporters was ransacked.        
	Local Trinamul Congress MLA Javed Ahmed Khan rushed to the spot as the situation was spinning out of control. A large contingent of police and Rapid Action Force personnel was called in to restore order. Vehicular movement on the Bypass connector was disrupted for 15 minutes. Traffic on Gobinda Khatik Road was suspended for an hour.        
	Local residents panicked after the violence broke out, with most traders downing shutters.        
	Rapid Action Force will patrol the area on Sunday night to prevent any further violence, said Vineet Goyal, the deputy commissioner of police, headquarters.                                                                                                                                                                         
